econet-eth: WHNAT TX probe -- Phase 0 fail-fast for WiFi HW-NAT

The WiFi HW-NAT port (replicating the OEM WHNAT scheme) hinges on one
irreducible hardware unknown: can our QDMA, given the OEM WiFi TX msg
(raw[0]=0x38 = channel 7/queue 0, raw[1]=0x200000 = WiFi fport, bit 21),
inject a frame into the PCIe-attached MT7603 so it transmits over the air?
This adds a minimal, self-contained probe to settle that before building any
infrastructure.

en75_whnat_tx_probe() builds a synthetic broadcast frame with a "WHNATPROBE"
marker, optionally inserts the WiFi mux VLAN tag, and posts it to qdma[0] (the
GDM1/conduit ring the OEM wifi_fast uses) with the WiFi msg. Knobs are exposed
as runtime-writable module params, so the whole test matrix sweeps without a
reload:

  whnat_tx_vid / tag / imm / msg0 / msg1, then: echo 1 > .../whnat_tx_fire

whnat_tx_imm ORs TX_IMMEDIATE_DONE into the qdma cfg live: the OEM sets it and
we don't (en75_init_final), and the WiFi egress yields no GDM "Done" -- so it
is the prime suspect for "descriptor posts but never completes". Observe with a
monitor sniffer on the AP channel (the AP must be wifi-up). Nothing here touches
the PPE/NAT datapath; it is a diagnostic, dropped once the path is productized.
